Reverse operation from v: binary(v) reversed gives us candidate strings that equal binary(x)+b (before stripping leading zeros). The stripped version is binary(v), so before stripping it could have had leading zeros. The reversed string of (binary(x)+b) = binary(v) with possible leading zeros prepended... 

Actually: `binary(v) = strip_leading_zeros(reverse(binary(x) + b))`. So `reverse(binary(x) + b)` = some leading zeros + binary(v). Thus `binary(x) + b = reverse(binary(v)) + some trailing zeros` - but that's not right either since reversing again...

`reverse(binary(x)+b)` starts with leading zeros then binary(v). So `binary(x)+b = reverse(leading_zeros + binary(v)) = reverse(binary(v)) + trailing_ones`... No.

`reverse(binary(x)+b) = 0...0 + binary(v)`, so `binary(x)+b = reverse(0...0 + binary(v)) = reverse(binary(v)) + 0...0`.

So `binary(x)+b` = `reverse(binary(v))` followed by k zeros, for k≥0. The last character is b (0 or 1). If k>0, then b=0 and the string is `reverse(binary(v))` + `0`*(k). But binary(x) must start with 1, so `reverse(binary(v))[0]` = 1, meaning `binary(v)` ends with 1. And we remove the last character to get binary(x).

For k=0: `binary(x)+b = reverse(binary(v))`, so binary(x) = reverse(binary(v))[:-1], b = last char of reverse(binary(v)) = first char of binary(v) = 1. This always works as long as reverse(binary(v))[:-1] starts with 1, i.e., binary(v) ends with 1... wait reverse(binary(v))[-2] = binary(v)[1] must be 1.

